---
# Symphony-TS workflow contract. Copy to WORKFLOW.md and customize.
tracker:
  kind: linear
  # Right-click your Linear project → Copy URL; the slug is the trailing segment.
  project_slug: "your-project-slug"
  # Reads LINEAR_API_KEY from the environment when api_key is unset or "$LINEAR_API_KEY".
  api_key: $LINEAR_API_KEY
  # Symphony custom flow — set these up in Linear: Team Settings → Workflow.
  active_states: [Todo, In Progress, Rework, Merging]
  terminal_states: [Done, Closed, Canceled, Cancelled, Duplicate]
  # Note: "Human Review" is intentionally NOT active — it parks work for a human.

polling:
  interval_ms: 5000

workspace:
  # Single shared repo (local path or git URL); every ticket gets a worktree off it.
  repo: git@github.com:your-org/your-repo.git
  root: ~/code/symphony-workspaces
  branch_prefix: "symphony/"

hooks:
  # Runs once per new worktree. Install deps here.
  after_create: |
    if [ -f package.json ]; then npm ci || npm install; fi
  timeout_ms: 120000

agent:
  backend: claude-sdk        # claude-sdk | claude-cli | codex-cli | opencode-cli
  permission_mode: bypassPermissions   # full autonomy (high-trust)
  max_concurrent_agents: 5
  max_turns: 20
  max_continuations: 50       # cap consecutive continuations before blocking the issue (0 = unlimited)
  # model: claude-opus-4-8   # optional override
  # max_budget_usd: 5        # optional per-turn budget cap (claude-sdk)
  # tmux: true               # CLI backends only: run each turn in a tmux session you can
                             # `tmux attach -t symphony-<id>`; raw stdout is logged to logs_root.
                             # No effect on the in-process claude-sdk backend.

# Root for raw tmux session logs (run.jsonl/err.log per turn). Default: <tmpdir>/symphony_logs.
# Override at launch with `--logs-root <dir>`.
# logs_root: ~/code/symphony-logs

server:
  port: 4500                 # enables the dashboard at http://127.0.0.1:4500/
---

You are an autonomous engineer working on Linear issue {{ issue.identifier }} in an isolated git
worktree on branch `symphony/{{ issue.identifier }}`.

Title: {{ issue.title }}
{% if issue.description %}
{{ issue.description }}
{% else %}
(No description provided.)
{% endif %}

Your job:
1. Implement the change end-to-end. Keep edits scoped to this issue.
2. Run the project's build/tests/lints and make them pass before finishing.
3. Commit your work to the current `symphony/{{ issue.identifier }}` branch with a concise message.
   Do NOT push or open a pull request — commits stay local for now.
4. Move the Linear issue to "Human Review" so a human can take it from here, and post a short
   comment summarizing what you changed. Use the `mcp__symphony__linear_graphql` tool (see below).
5. If you are blocked and genuinely need a human decision, say so explicitly and stop — do not guess.

You have a `mcp__symphony__linear_graphql` tool that runs ONE raw Linear GraphQL query/mutation
with Symphony's configured auth. Linear's `issueUpdate` needs the target state's **ID (a UUID), not
its name**, so always resolve the id first:

a. Look up this issue's team workflow states and find the one named "Human Review":
   `query { issue(id: "{{ issue.id }}") { team { states { nodes { id name } } } } }`
b. Move the issue using that id:
   `mutation { issueUpdate(id: "{{ issue.id }}", input: { stateId: "<STATE_UUID>" }) { success } }`
c. Post your summary:
   `mutation { commentCreate(input: { issueId: "{{ issue.id }}", body: "..." }) { success } }`

Pass each operation as a single GraphQL document; call the tool once per operation.
